\begin{abstract}
We study $^{87}$ Rb cold collisions in a static magnetic field and a single - color radio frequency ( RF ) field by employing the multi-channel quantum defect theory in combination with the Floquet method to solve the two - body time - dependent Schr\ " odinger equation .
Our results show that RF fields can modify the two - body scattering length by a large scale through Feshbach resonances both in low and high static magnetic field regimes .
Such RF induced Feshbach resonances can be applied to quenching experiments or controlling interactions in spinor condensates .
Here , we also show that analogous to photo - association , RF fields can also associate cold atoms into molecules at a useful rate .
\end{abstract}

In the RF induced bound - bound transition scenario , RF photons drive transitions between two weakly bound molecules .
The bare Rabi frequency between two weakly bound molecules , which characterizes the strength of the transition in zero detuning , is given by % is proportional to the bound - bound Rabi frequency which is given by
\begin{equation}
\hbar\Omega= | \langle\psi_{b1}|\vec{\mu} \cdot \vec{B}_{RF}|\psi_{b2}\rangle |,
\end{equation}
where $\vec{\mu}=(\vec{\mu}_1+\vec{\mu}_2)$ is the total magnetic moment of two free atoms , $\psi_{b1}$ and $\psi_{b2}$ are bound state wave functions including all spin and spatial degrees of freedom .

